04721nam a22006255i 9780822377764DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19991999ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223777647 a10.1515/97808223777642doi  a(DE-B1597)553739  a(OCoLC)893680847  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPR448.C64bA73 1999 7aLIT0041202bisacsh1 aAravamudan, Srinivas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTropicopolitans :bColonialism and Agency, 1688-1804 /cSrinivas Aravamudan. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (440 p.) :b28 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Colonialism and Eighteenth-Century Studies -- tVirtualizations -- tONE. Petting Oroonoko -- tTWO. Piratical Accounts -- tTHREE. The Stoic's Voice -- tLevantinizations -- tFOUR. Lady Mary in the Hammam -- tFIVE. The Despotic Eye and the Oriental Sublime -- tNationalizations -- tSIX. Equiano and the Politics of Literacy -- tSEVEN. Tropicalizing the Enlightenment -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Tropicopolitans Srinivas Aravamudan reconstructs the colonial imagination of the eighteenth century. By exploring representations of peoples and cultures subjected to colonial discourse, he makes a case for the agency-or the capacity to resist domination-of those oppressed. Aravamudan's analysis of texts that accompanied European commercial and imperial expansion from the Glorious Revolution through the French Revolution reveals the development of anticolonial consciousness prior to the nineteenth century."Tropicalization" is the central metaphor of this analysis, a term that incorporates both the construction of various dynamic tropes by which the colonized are viewed and the site of the study, primarily the tropics. Tropicopolitans, then, are those people who bear and resist the representations of colonialist discourse. In readings that expose new relationships between literary representation and colonialism in the eighteenth century, Aravamudan considers such texts as Behn's Oroonoko, Defoe's Robinson Crusoe and Captain Singleton, Addison's Cato, and Swift's Gulliver's Travels and The Drapier's Letters. He extends his argument to include analyses of Johnson's Rasselas, Beckford's Vathek, Montagu's travel letters, Equiano's autobiography, Burke's political and aesthetic writings, and Abbé de Raynal's Histoire des deux Indes. Offering a radical approach to literary history, this study provides new mechanisms for understanding the development of anticolonial agency.Introducing eighteenth-century studies to a postcolonial hermeneutics, Tropicopolitans will interest scholars engaged in postcolonial studies, eighteenth-century literature, and literary theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aBlacks in literature. 0aColonies in literature. 0aColoniesxHistory. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aNationalism and literaturexColonieszFrancexHistory. 0aNationalism and literaturexColonieszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aSlavery in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822377764zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822377764423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822377764.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archiv